<cell id="cell-0"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type># Make a synthetic twin of any dataset (no LLM, no API key)

You have a dataset you can't share: customer records, patient rows, anything with names and money in it. You still need data that behaves like it for demos, tests, tutorials, and model prototyping.

This notebook shows three things, all running entirely inside this kernel:

1. **`misata.mimic()`**: point it at a CSV and get a synthetic twin that matches the distributions but contains none of the original rows — including tricky columns like Ticket codes, Cabin identifiers, and float Fares that keep their cents.
2. **`misata.generate()`**: skip the source data entirely. Describe the dataset you want, including the numbers it must hit, and a deterministic math engine builds it.
3. **Declared outcome curves**: tell Misata "revenue grows from $50k to $200k" and the generated rows sum to those targets exactly, to the cent, verifiable with a single `groupby`.

[Misata](https://github.com/rasinmuhammed/misata) is an open-source Python library (MIT). The generation engine is pure math: seeded, vectorized NumPy. No model call, no tokens, nothing leaves the kernel. The mechanism behind its exact-outcome guarantee is formalized in [this arXiv paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.08736).</cell>
<cell id="cell-1">%pip install -q misata
import warnings; warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")
import misata
print("misata", misata.__version__)</cell>
<cell id="cell-2"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## Part 1: the synthetic twin

We'll use the Titanic dataset because everyone on Kaggle knows its shape. Swap in any CSV you like: `misata.mimic()` profiles every column (distribution fit, cardinality, date ranges, semantic type) and generates fresh rows from the profile, never from the data.</cell>
<cell id="cell-3">import pandas as pd
from pathlib import Path

# On Kaggle the Titanic competition data lives under /kaggle/input.
kaggle_path = Path("/kaggle/input/titanic/train.csv")
if kaggle_path.exists():
    real = pd.read_csv(kaggle_path)
else:
    real = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/datasciencedojo/datasets/master/titanic.csv")

real[["Name", "Ticket", "Cabin", "Fare"]].head(5)</cell>
<cell id="cell-4">twin = misata.mimic(real, rows=2000, seed=42, table_name="passengers")["passengers"]
twin[["Name", "Ticket", "Cabin", "Fare"]].head(5)</cell>
<cell id="cell-5"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>### The columns that trip up other synthesizers

`Ticket` has values like `"A/5 21171"`, `"PC 17599"`, `"349207"` — alphanumeric code shapes, not prose. `Cabin` is `"C85"`, `"B28"`, `"E46"`. `Fare` is `7.25`, `71.2833`, `8.0458` — cents matter.

Misata's profiler detects code-shaped columns (short, identifier charset, digit-heavy) and infers their character-class skeletons. The twin reproduces each shape in the right proportions, generates entirely new values, and never copies a verbatim row from the source.</cell>
<cell id="cell-6">import re

# Ticket shapes present in the real data
real_shapes = set(
    re.sub(r"[A-Z]", "L", re.sub(r"[a-z]", "l", re.sub(r"\d", "d", str(t))))
    for t in real["Ticket"].dropna()
)
twin_shapes = set(
    re.sub(r"[A-Z]", "L", re.sub(r"[a-z]", "l", re.sub(r"\d", "d", str(t))))
    for t in twin["Ticket"].dropna()
)

print("Ticket shapes in real data:      ", sorted(real_shapes)[:6])
print("Ticket shapes in twin:            ", sorted(twin_shapes)[:6])

# Fares keep their decimal places
print(f"\nReal  Fare decimals present: {(real['Fare'].dropna() % 1 != 0).mean():.0%}")
print(f"Twin  Fare decimals present: {(twin['Fare'].dropna() % 1 != 0).mean():.0%}")

# And zero verbatim tickets leak through
shared_tickets = set(real["Ticket"].dropna()) & set(twin["Ticket"].dropna())
print(f"\nVerbatim tickets in both real and twin: {len(shared_tickets)}")</cell>
<cell id="cell-7"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>### Does the twin behave like the original on the things that matter for ML?

Overlay the numeric distributions.</cell>
<cell id="cell-8">import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

numeric = [c for c in ["Age", "Fare"] if c in real.columns and c in twin.columns]
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, len(numeric), figsize=(11, 3.5))
for ax, colname in zip(axes, numeric):
    ax.hist(real[colname].dropna(), bins=30, alpha=0.55, label="real", density=True)
    ax.hist(twin[colname].dropna(), bins=30, alpha=0.55, label="synthetic", density=True)
    ax.set_title(colname)
    ax.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()</cell>
<cell id="cell-9"># Categorical balance survives too.
for colname in [c for c in ["Pclass", "Sex", "Embarked"] if c in real.columns]:
    cmp = pd.DataFrame({
        "real": real[colname].value_counts(normalize=True).round(3),
        "synthetic": twin[colname].value_counts(normalize=True).round(3),
    })
    print(cmp, "\n")</cell>
<cell id="cell-10"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>### The privacy check

The twin is sampled from fitted distributions, not resampled from rows. No original record can leak into it:</cell>
<cell id="cell-11">shared = [c for c in real.columns if c in twin.columns]
overlap = pd.merge(real[shared].astype(str), twin[shared].astype(str), how="inner")
print(f"identical rows shared between real and twin: {len(overlap)}")</cell>
<cell id="cell-12"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## Part 2: no source data, declared outcomes

Mimic needs a CSV. The more powerful path is declaring what the data must look like — including the exact numbers it must hit — and having the engine build relational tables that satisfy those targets to the cent.

Here we build a SaaS dataset and declare that monthly recurring revenue rises from $50k in January to $200k in December.</cell>
<cell id="cell-13">import misata

schema = misata.from_dict_schema({
    "__outcome_curves__": [{
        "table": "subscriptions",
        "column": "mrr",
        "time_column": "billing_date",
        "time_unit": "month",
        "value_mode": "absolute",
        "start_date": "2024-01-01",
        "avg_transaction_value": 150.0,
        "curve_points": [
            {"month": 1,  "target_value":  50_000.0},
            {"month": 3,  "target_value":  75_000.0},
            {"month": 6,  "target_value": 110_000.0},
            {"month": 9,  "target_value": 160_000.0},
            {"month": 12, "target_value": 200_000.0},
        ],
    }],
    "users": {
        "__rows__": 2000,
        "user_id":    {"type": "integer", "primary_key": True},
        "email":      {"type": "email"},
        "plan":       {"type": "string", "enum": ["free", "pro", "enterprise"],
                       "probabilities": [0.6, 0.3, 0.1]},
        "created_at": {"type": "date"},
    },
    "subscriptions": {
        "__rows__": 5000,
        "sub_id":       {"type": "integer", "primary_key": True},
        "user_id":      {"type": "integer",
                         "foreign_key": {"table": "users", "column": "user_id"}},
        "mrr":          {"type": "float", "min": 29, "max": 999},
        "billing_date": {"type": "date"},
    },
}, seed=42)

tables = misata.generate_from_schema(schema)
print({name: len(df) for name, df in tables.items()})</cell>
<cell id="cell-14"># Verify the declared curve was hit exactly.
subs = tables["subscriptions"]
monthly = (
    subs.assign(month=pd.to_datetime(subs["billing_date"]).dt.month)
    .groupby("month")["mrr"].sum()
)

targets = {1: 50_000, 3: 75_000, 6: 110_000, 9: 160_000, 12: 200_000}
print(f"{'month':>6}  {'declared':>12}  {'generated':>12}  {'delta':>8}")
for m, target in targets.items():
    actual = monthly.get(m, 0)
    print(f"{m:>6}  {target:>12,.2f}  {actual:>12,.2f}  {actual - target:>+8.2f}")</cell>
<cell id="cell-15"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>Every declared month lands at exactly $0.00 error. Not approximately — the conformance is closed-form, formalised in [arXiv:2606.08736](https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.08736).

This is the property that makes Misata useful for anything beyond demos: you can write assertions against the generated data and they will pass every time, on any machine, with the same seed.</cell>
<cell id="cell-16"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>## Part 3: plain English, no schema

For competition work where you want data shaped like a real domain but with no source CSV and no schema authoring, one sentence is enough:</cell>
<cell id="cell-17">tables = misata.generate(
    "A fintech with 2,000 customers, checking and savings accounts, "
    "and 20,000 transactions including a 2% fraud rate.",
    seed=42,
)

transactions = tables["transactions"]
accounts = tables["accounts"]

print({name: len(df) for name, df in tables.items()})
print(f"\norphan FK rows:  {(~transactions['account_id'].isin(accounts['account_id'])).sum()}")
print(f"fraud rate:      {transactions['is_fraud'].mean():.4f}")</cell>
<cell id="cell-18"><cell_type>markdown</cell_type>Referential integrity holds across every FK. The declared fraud rate lands within rounding of the target.

---

## Why this matters for ML on Kaggle

- **Class balance on demand.** Declare 2%, 10%, or 50% fraud. No SMOTE, no resampling artifacts.
- **Reproducible by construction.** Same seed, same bytes, every kernel rerun, every teammate's machine.
- **Relational, not just tabular.** Parents generate before children; every join behaves like production data.
- **Declared outcomes.** If your notebook claims "revenue grew from $50k to $200k", the underlying dataset can literally prove it — not approximately, verifiably.
- **Code columns stay code columns.** Ticket identifiers, Cabin codes, SKUs, reference numbers all reproduce as structurally correct new values, not product-description text.

